WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.670 --> 00:00:05.310
CHRIS: It's my distinct pleasure
to welcome Professor Paul

00:00:05.310 --> 00:00:12.950
Sabin who is an environmental
and energy historian at Yale.

00:00:12.950 --> 00:00:16.059
It's my distinct pleasure to
welcome him to Google so please

00:00:16.059 --> 00:00:18.200
join me in giving him
a round of applause.

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:21.827
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:21.827 --> 00:00:22.910
PAUL SABIN: Thanks, Chris.

00:00:22.910 --> 00:00:26.380
And thanks for having
me here at Google.

00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:29.234
Americans love history, but
I think in this business

00:00:29.234 --> 00:00:30.650
and technology
setting, it's worth

00:00:30.650 --> 00:00:33.741
asking what history is good for.

00:00:33.741 --> 00:00:35.490
And I want to emphasize
a couple of things

00:00:35.490 --> 00:00:37.290
in starting out around that.

00:00:37.290 --> 00:00:38.870
One is just the way
that history can

00:00:38.870 --> 00:00:43.200
help us to appreciate complexity
and the uncertainty of the past

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:46.270
and also the way in which
it can help us to develop

00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:49.390
a way that we can cultivate
empathy for the people whose

00:00:49.390 --> 00:00:53.390
lives we're studying and
whose decisions and choices

00:00:53.390 --> 00:00:55.820
we're trying to understand.

00:00:55.820 --> 00:00:58.980
I think these two different
kinds of understanding

00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:00.600
can help us cultivate
our listening,

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:03.590
can foster a critical
sense of humility,

00:01:03.590 --> 00:01:05.280
and also they can
raise questions for us

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:07.721
to ask about the future.

00:01:07.721 --> 00:01:09.220
More generally, I
think that history

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:12.100
can offer a sense of
context and perspective

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:15.160
that's necessary for the
challenging social choices

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:17.490
that I believe we have
to make in charting

00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:19.740
our future on the planet.

00:01:19.740 --> 00:01:23.310
Now, science and technology
and economics obviously all

00:01:23.310 --> 00:01:27.640
have a critical role
to play in this future.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:29.906
But I think that they
don't have all the answers.

00:01:29.906 --> 00:01:31.530
And they don't
necessarily even prepare

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:33.920
us to know what
questions to ask.

00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:38.214
So that's where I think history
can play a critical role.

00:01:38.214 --> 00:01:39.880
So I want to circle
back to these themes

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:42.370
at the close of my talk,
to talk a little bit

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:44.590
about the interesting
and complex ways in which

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:46.820
the story that I'm
going to share today

00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:50.280
has been interpreted and the
way people have reacted to--

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:52.380
and let me just say
I guess as a hint

00:01:52.380 --> 00:01:57.100
that listening and humility
are not the keywords that

00:01:57.100 --> 00:02:01.102
come to mind in thinking
about that interpretation.

00:02:01.102 --> 00:02:02.810
So today I want to
tell you a story based

00:02:02.810 --> 00:02:06.420
on my recent book, "The Bet:
Paul Ehrlich, Julian Simon,

00:02:06.420 --> 00:02:08.860
and Our Gamble Over
Earth's Future."

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:10.430
And my goal is
really to provide you

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:14.180
with some perspective on the
growing partisanship that

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:17.750
has come to engulf our debate
over environmental issues

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:19.260
in the United States.

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:20.700
And this is really
to help us also

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:25.580
think more about risks of
environmental catastrophe

00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:27.530
and resource scarcity
on the one hand

00:02:27.530 --> 00:02:30.820
and also the promise of
technological innovation

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:35.010
and human ingenuity and
progress, human advancement

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:36.520
into the future.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:39.729
So this is a story about
sharply disagreeing viewpoints.

00:02:39.729 --> 00:02:41.770
But as I'll say at the
end, I think the challenge

00:02:41.770 --> 00:02:43.270
for us really is
to try to find ways

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:47.330
to reconcile these different
viewpoints and learn from them.

00:02:47.330 --> 00:02:50.110
Now, we weren't always as
divided as we are today.

00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:52.410
Just this week, you had the
Senate Democrats pulling

00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:55.990
an all nighter to talk
about climate issues,

00:02:55.990 --> 00:02:59.150
and on the other side,
you have many Republicans

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:04.160
who are questioning whether
climate change is caused

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:08.930
by humans or to what extent
it's changing and opposing

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:11.990
many of the initiatives that
EPA-- a job-killing agency

00:03:11.990 --> 00:03:13.304
it's been called.

00:03:13.304 --> 00:03:14.970
So we weren't always
as divided as this,

00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:16.344
and I think it's
worth going back

00:03:16.344 --> 00:03:19.020
to remember some of the
bipartisanship with which

00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:23.480
the environmental legislation
of the 1970s was passed.

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:25.645
The Clean Air Act,
the Clean Water Act,

00:03:25.645 --> 00:03:27.770
the National Environmental
Policy Act, all of these

00:03:27.770 --> 00:03:32.490
were passed with bipartisan
support in Congress.

00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:36.270
And Richard Nixon
actually articulated

00:03:36.270 --> 00:03:40.420
this bipartisan attitude in
his 1970 state of the union.

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:42.430
And I wanted to
share, if I can here,

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:45.160
a little video from
him in which he talks

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:48.362
about how a concern
for the environment

00:03:48.362 --> 00:03:50.070
was something that
should be beyond party

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:51.090
and beyond faction.

00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:54.520
So this is Richard Nixon
talking in the 1970s

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:56.616
state of the union.

00:03:56.616 --> 00:03:57.520
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:03:57.520 --> 00:04:00.040
-The great question
to the '70s is,

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:03.594
shall we surrender
to our surroundings

00:04:03.594 --> 00:04:07.042
or shall we make our
peace with nature

00:04:07.042 --> 00:04:10.206
and begin to make reparations
for the damage we have done

00:04:10.206 --> 00:04:13.970
to our air, to our
land, and to our water?

00:04:13.970 --> 00:04:19.709
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:19.709 --> 00:04:21.649
Restoring nature to
it's natural state

00:04:21.649 --> 00:04:25.940
is a cause beyond party
and beyond factions.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:29.970
It has become a common cause of
all the people of this country.

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:34.200
It is a cause of particular
concern to young Americans

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:38.770
because they more than we will
reap the grim consequences

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:42.245
of our failure to act on
programs which are needed now

00:04:42.245 --> 00:04:45.060
if we are to prevent
disaster later.

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:48.553
Clean air, clean
water, open spaces,

00:04:48.553 --> 00:04:49.867
these should once again--

00:04:49.867 --> 00:04:50.700
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:52.908
PAUL SABIN: So this is Nixon
with a unifying message,

00:04:52.908 --> 00:04:54.930
bringing people together
around the environment.

00:04:54.930 --> 00:05:00.260
And he didn't necessarily stay
in this point of view for long.

00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:02.745
He became a little
disillusioned with how well

00:05:02.745 --> 00:05:05.220
the environmental cause was
serving him politically.

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:08.616
And he wasn't necessarily a
passionate environmentalist.

00:05:08.616 --> 00:05:10.490
Here's a picture of him
walking on the beach.

00:05:10.490 --> 00:05:11.864
He was trying to
be Kennedy-esque

00:05:11.864 --> 00:05:14.010
walking on the beach
in Southern California

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:18.080
but with his wing tip
shoes and his dress pants.

00:05:18.080 --> 00:05:20.830
But still, even Nixon was
bringing people together

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:22.030
around the environment.

00:05:22.030 --> 00:05:26.020
And so that was in the early
1970s, but by the 1980s,

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.750
you had a gradually
growing division,

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:31.060
greater partisanship
around the environment.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:35.130
And you can see that in these
League of Conservation scores

00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:36.410
by chamber and party.

00:05:36.410 --> 00:05:39.430
You can see kind of a gradually
opening gulf between the two

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:43.610
parties on the votes
that they were cataloging

00:05:43.610 --> 00:05:48.910
in Congress for this index.

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:53.070
So what are the explanations
for this growing partisanship

00:05:53.070 --> 00:05:54.260
around the environment?

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:56.840
There are several
common explanations.

00:05:56.840 --> 00:05:59.860
Some have explained it in part
as the sifting out of the two

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:03.325
parties by region and
according to ideology,

00:06:03.325 --> 00:06:04.950
where the Southern
Democrats moved over

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:07.730
to the Republican Party and
the northern Republicans

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:10.680
moved over to the
Democrat and kind of took

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:13.370
their environmental
affiliations with them.

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:15.820
Others have explained it as
more of a business backlash,

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:18.680
with business interests
fighting regulation and pushing

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:22.500
their political allies to
contest regulatory initiatives.

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:25.640
And still others have identified
a conservative intellectual

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:28.930
revolution with think
tanks and funding

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:30.640
for public intellectuals
who would then

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:34.530
advance criticism of
environmental regulation.

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:37.300
I think all of these
different explanations

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:38.820
have some truth to them.

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:42.660
And scholars have
examined them in depth.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:46.040
But at the same time, I think
that these interpretations

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:48.120
don't say the whole story.

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:51.315
And what I want to explore
today is the genuine clash

00:06:51.315 --> 00:06:55.180
that occurred between different
viewpoints in the 1970s

00:06:55.180 --> 00:06:58.100
and 1980s because these
interpretations really

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:00.790
explain the growing
partisanship primarily

00:07:00.790 --> 00:07:04.040
as just a political and economic
development, that people are

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.330
representing their political
and economic interest.

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:08.330
And they tend not
to look more closely

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:11.650
at the intellectual
conflicts and what

00:07:11.650 --> 00:07:13.510
I see as some of the
weaknesses and flaws

00:07:13.510 --> 00:07:16.030
of the environmental
movement during this period.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:18.070
So I think that's a mistake.

00:07:18.070 --> 00:07:21.440
And in my book, "The
Bet," I revisit the rise

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:23.780
of the environmental
movement since the 1960s

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:26.620
and the backlash and the
debates that it engendered.

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:30.570
And so I approach this story
through a smaller story

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:35.050
that I think allows entry into
the larger debates happening

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:36.920
in environmental politics.

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.870
And this was a story about the
biologist Paul Ehrlich, here

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:45.480
on your left, author of the
1968 book "The Population Bomb,"

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.780
and his antagonist Julian
Simon on the right,

00:07:48.780 --> 00:07:50.990
who wrote the book "The
Ultimate Resource."

00:07:50.990 --> 00:07:53.890
And these two men
made an actual bet,

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:56.700
which is a rare thing in
intellectual disagreements.

00:07:56.700 --> 00:08:00.840
They came together around a
bet over metal prices in 1980.

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:05.100
And it was a simple bet over
five metals, chromium, copper,

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.730
tin, nickel, and tungsten.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:11.690
It was a bundle of those
metals worth a total of $1,000.

00:08:11.690 --> 00:08:14.420
And, essentially,
if the prices rose,

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:17.130
Simon would pay the difference
and if the prices fell,

00:08:17.130 --> 00:08:19.730
Ehrlich and his
colleagues would pay.

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:22.720
And it was going to
be a 10 year bet.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:25.180
Now, it was a simple
bet about metal prices,

00:08:25.180 --> 00:08:27.850
but really the bet
stood for much more.

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:29.730
It was really a proxy
for their competing

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:30.800
visions of the future.

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:34.460
On Ehrlich's side, an
apocalyptic vision that

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:39.190
was fearful about human
excess and over population.

00:08:39.190 --> 00:08:41.789
And on Simon's side,
optimistic and bullish

00:08:41.789 --> 00:08:44.870
about the potential
for human progress.

00:08:44.870 --> 00:08:46.770
Ehrlich thought that
rising metal prices

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:50.990
would signify that population
growth caused resource

00:08:50.990 --> 00:08:52.360
scarcity.

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:56.310
And that would bolster his call
for government-led population

00:08:56.310 --> 00:08:59.400
control and limits
on consumption.

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:02.740
Simon argued that markets
and new technology

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:04.470
would drive prices down.

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:06.730
And this would prove
that society did not

00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:10.440
face resource constraints and
that human welfare, in fact,

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:12.750
was going to steadily improve.

00:09:12.750 --> 00:09:15.520
And so the outcome of the
small bet about metal prices

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:18.500
would have these tremendous
implications for what direction

00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:22.380
the planet and
humanity was headed in.

00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:24.620
It would either
bolster Ehrlich's call

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:27.640
for limits on population
growth and his warnings

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:29.310
of an environmental calamity.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:33.390
Or it would fuel
Simon's attack on what

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:37.870
he called Ehrlich's
"unfounded threats of doom."

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:40.460
So in the book I try, in
the spirit of the empathy

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:43.850
that I talked about and
the complexity, to explore

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:46.000
these two men and
their different lives

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.530
and how they arrived at the
positions that they took.

00:09:48.530 --> 00:09:51.364
And I want to talk a
little bit about that

00:09:51.364 --> 00:09:52.780
because Ehrlich
and Simon actually

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:55.269
are very interesting characters
who shared much in common.

00:09:55.269 --> 00:09:57.310
Actually, in some ways,
that was what drove them,

00:09:57.310 --> 00:09:59.630
I think, to such
sharp disagreement.

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:03.690
They both were born in 1932
to Jewish families that

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:05.730
were based originally
in the cities,

00:10:05.730 --> 00:10:09.010
in Philadelphia and in
Newark, but then moved out

00:10:09.010 --> 00:10:13.010
into the suburbs
just before they

00:10:13.010 --> 00:10:14.827
each were around 10 years old.

00:10:14.827 --> 00:10:16.410
And they actually
grew up about three,

00:10:16.410 --> 00:10:18.390
five miles apart from
each other in Maplewood,

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:20.880
and Millburn, New Jersey.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:24.590
Ehrlich was a child of
the suburbs in the sense

00:10:24.590 --> 00:10:29.150
that he loved chasing
butterflies through the fields

00:10:29.150 --> 00:10:32.970
and he was impassioned about
the threat of development

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:34.520
to the suburban landscape.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:36.910
He became early on
concerned about the danger

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:41.200
of DDT, the pesticide being
sprayed that was endangering

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:45.960
the food sources that he wanted
to feed to his butterflies.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:50.270
He was a lover of nature.

00:10:50.270 --> 00:10:52.700
At one point, he had so many
aquariums and other types

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:54.540
of collections in
his bedroom that he

00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:57.850
had to move out and
move up into the attic

00:10:57.850 --> 00:11:00.690
to make room for them.

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:02.590
So Ehrlich's study
of butterflies,

00:11:02.590 --> 00:11:04.770
which he's continued as
a professor up the road

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:09.080
here at Stanford-- this
is the Bay Checkerspot

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:12.110
butterfly-- really
provided him with a model

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:13.980
for thinking about
human population growth

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:17.660
because he studied the rise and
fall of butterfly populations

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:21.670
in relationship to the abundance
and scarcity of resources.

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:24.980
And so, in seeing that
butterfly populations might grow

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:28.910
and then they might outstrip the
resources that were available

00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:31.490
and then they would crash in
this tremendous collapse--

00:11:31.490 --> 00:11:33.364
and then he said this
was the same thing that

00:11:33.364 --> 00:11:35.280
was going to happen to people.

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:39.670
And so he predicted the greatest
cataclysm in the history of man

00:11:39.670 --> 00:11:42.090
was coming, this
population collapse

00:11:42.090 --> 00:11:47.100
that would be caused by food
shortages, disease outbreaks,

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:49.670
maybe thermonuclear war.

00:11:49.670 --> 00:11:53.636
And he described
that the population

00:11:53.636 --> 00:11:55.010
had grown to the
extent-- he said

00:11:55.010 --> 00:11:57.610
we've had most of what he called
the outbreak of population

00:11:57.610 --> 00:12:00.130
and now all that
we're waiting for is

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:02.000
what's going to
come in the crash.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.390
So kind of basically modeling
onto human populations

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:07.775
the same developments
as with butterflies

00:12:07.775 --> 00:12:08.650
and other creatures.

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:09.710
And he wasn't alone in this.

00:12:09.710 --> 00:12:11.835
There were many biologists
in the post World War Ii

00:12:11.835 --> 00:12:17.350
period who were thinking about
animal populations in this way.

00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:21.650
Ehrlich was so concerned about
the threat of population growth

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:24.320
that he came to embrace
the idea of triage,

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:28.050
that some countries
might be so far gone,

00:12:28.050 --> 00:12:30.209
so headed directly
towards catastrophe

00:12:30.209 --> 00:12:32.500
and unable to feed themselves
that they should actually

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:33.800
be cut off from food aid.

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:37.380
And he put countries like
India in this category,

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:39.520
saying the US should
no longer send them

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:42.430
food aid because quote,
"dispassionate analysis

00:12:42.430 --> 00:12:45.700
indicates that the unbalance
between food and population

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:47.150
is hopeless."

00:12:47.150 --> 00:12:52.040
And he argued that the optimum
human worldwide population

00:12:52.040 --> 00:12:55.880
was somewhere between 600
million and 1.5 billion people,

00:12:55.880 --> 00:12:59.470
so significantly less than what
even the population was then

00:12:59.470 --> 00:13:02.130
around 1968, 1970.

00:13:02.130 --> 00:13:05.140
Now, Ehrlich was a very
popular, charismatic speaker

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:07.140
with a biting wit,
very entertaining.

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:11.310
Here he is speaking to students
around Earth Day at Iowa State

00:13:11.310 --> 00:13:12.150
University.

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:14.750
He spoke to audiences
of thousands.

00:13:14.750 --> 00:13:18.000
And in 1970, he
really became famous

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.920
after Johnny Carson invited
him onto "The Tonight Show,"

00:13:21.920 --> 00:13:25.086
became a big fan of his,
loved having him on the show

00:13:25.086 --> 00:13:26.710
and had him actually
more than 20 times

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:29.080
onto "The Tonight
Show" and really shared

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:32.226
a lot of his views on population
and environmental issues

00:13:32.226 --> 00:13:33.350
and gave him that platform.

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:37.720
That really brought Ehrlich
to much greater fame.

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:40.280
Now, Julian Simon,
as I said, also

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:42.900
grew up in suburban New
Jersey in his teenage years.

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:45.370
But his formative years
were really in Newark.

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:49.770
And he was impressed in
the early age the hustle

00:13:49.770 --> 00:13:50.990
and bustle of immigrant life.

00:13:50.990 --> 00:13:52.490
And he loved the
diversity of people

00:13:52.490 --> 00:13:54.156
and the excitement
of being in the city,

00:13:54.156 --> 00:13:55.790
and he always,
after he moved out

00:13:55.790 --> 00:13:59.830
into the suburbs-- he regretted
the loss of that community

00:13:59.830 --> 00:14:02.540
that he had felt when
he had been in Newark.

00:14:02.540 --> 00:14:05.600
And I think that carried through
in his appreciation of cities

00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:08.010
and people and more people
bringing more excitement

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:12.000
and diversity to the world.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.870
He took a slightly more
circuitous path into academia.

00:14:14.870 --> 00:14:18.640
Here he is as a Boy
Scout as a young boy.

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:21.844
He served in the Navy
for a few years also,

00:14:21.844 --> 00:14:24.010
giving him an impression
of what the world was like.

00:14:24.010 --> 00:14:26.280
And what he saw
later would describe

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:30.020
some of the more rundown
areas of the world

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:32.122
where his Navy ship
would stop and thinking

00:14:32.122 --> 00:14:34.580
about how they had improved
over time, that you didn't just

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:35.850
see the beautiful
parts of the world

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:36.890
but there were
these other places

00:14:36.890 --> 00:14:39.570
that he had seen and saw the
improvements that took place

00:14:39.570 --> 00:14:40.410
there.

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:44.190
Now, Simon early on actually
shared Ehrlich's view

00:14:44.190 --> 00:14:46.190
about the threat of
population growth.

00:14:46.190 --> 00:14:49.310
And he got into studying
marketing and business.

00:14:49.310 --> 00:14:51.830
And he was hired by I
think it was the Population

00:14:51.830 --> 00:14:54.810
Council to develop
marketing plans for family

00:14:54.810 --> 00:14:57.855
planning in India
and in other places.

00:14:57.855 --> 00:14:59.730
And so he was originally
trying to figure out

00:14:59.730 --> 00:15:03.530
how to address the problem
of population growth.

00:15:03.530 --> 00:15:06.340
But then he came to believe
that actually population growth

00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:07.240
wasn't a problem.

00:15:07.240 --> 00:15:10.360
And in this, he sort of linked
up with some other economists

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:14.710
at the time, people like Simon
Kuznets and Richard Easterlin.

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:17.930
And they had examined historical
patterns of economic growth

00:15:17.930 --> 00:15:20.137
and correlated them
with population growth

00:15:20.137 --> 00:15:21.720
and decided that
there wasn't actually

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:24.260
evidence that population
growth was diminishing

00:15:24.260 --> 00:15:25.990
national economic growth.

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:29.020
And you also people like the
Danish agricultural economist

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:34.900
Ester Boserup, who found that
population growth actually

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:38.650
increased innovation in
agriculture and spurred saving.

00:15:38.650 --> 00:15:42.471
And so rather than
agriculture setting limits

00:15:42.471 --> 00:15:44.720
for population, which was
the idea that there was only

00:15:44.720 --> 00:15:46.275
so much that
agriculture produced.

00:15:46.275 --> 00:15:48.400
She actually found that it
was sort of the reverse.

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:51.130
It was the density and
the demand of population

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:53.700
that set limits on
agriculture and that the forms

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:57.125
of agriculture were determined,
in part, by population size

00:15:57.125 --> 00:15:58.750
and density and that
it would stimulate

00:15:58.750 --> 00:16:02.350
new kinds of
agricultural practices.

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:06.270
Now in 1980, Simon broke
out into the public arena

00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:09.740
with a article in "Science"
in which he attacked

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:12.670
Ehrlich and other
doom-sayers for what he said

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:17.350
were unfounded-- the
oversupply of false bad news.

00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:19.820
And he soon found common
cause with libertarians

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:23.720
and conservatives and
enjoyed a lot of attention

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:25.800
as a regular contributor
to op-ed pages

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:28.710
with these kinds of
arguments-- that life on Earth

00:16:28.710 --> 00:16:31.350
is improving, that these
myths of overpopulation.

00:16:31.350 --> 00:16:34.040
"Why Do We Think
Babies Create Poverty?"

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:35.530
So these are all
part of a campaign

00:16:35.530 --> 00:16:38.200
to change the way that people
thought about population

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:40.230
growth, and he
then extended this

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:42.640
as well to the problem
of immigration.

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.410
And this is where actually--
these characters, these

00:16:45.410 --> 00:16:47.340
are individual
intellectuals navigating

00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:49.700
the currents of
American politics--

00:16:49.700 --> 00:16:52.420
in which he sort of fell
out with many American

00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:53.920
conservatives because
Simon actually

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:57.750
was quite pro-immigration,
believing that immigrants were

00:16:57.750 --> 00:17:00.310
an asset to the American
economy and would

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:01.520
stimulate economic growth.

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:03.270
They took much less
than they contributed.

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.085
And so he was an early
advocate for immigration.

00:17:06.085 --> 00:17:07.960
So actually there was
recently the suggestion

00:17:07.960 --> 00:17:10.310
that Detroit should create
a special economic zone

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:12.829
and invite immigrants
to come in who

00:17:12.829 --> 00:17:15.579
would invest to create
jobs in the city.

00:17:15.579 --> 00:17:20.300
This was the kind of thing
that Simon was in favor of.

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:23.700
And actually just as
an aside, you may never

00:17:23.700 --> 00:17:26.170
have heard of Julian
Simon before today,

00:17:26.170 --> 00:17:30.500
but one of the things
that he's more known for--

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:32.560
or you would know
him for-- is that he

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:36.530
was one of the main advocates
for the idea of an auction

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:39.506
for overbooking on airlines,
that you should have a market.

00:17:39.506 --> 00:17:41.380
So if you have ever been
bumped from a flight

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:44.950
and gotten a free flight or
some other benefit as a result,

00:17:44.950 --> 00:17:47.840
that was one of the ideas that
Julian Simon was an advocate

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:49.560
for.

00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:51.960
So if Simon sort of fell
out with conservatives

00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:53.930
over his position
on immigration,

00:17:53.930 --> 00:17:56.680
Ehrlich also had sort of
a complicated relationship

00:17:56.680 --> 00:17:58.250
to liberals.

00:17:58.250 --> 00:18:02.480
And he came under attack
for being racist, being

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:04.720
anti-immigrant, those
types of questions

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:06.710
about what was his position.

00:18:06.710 --> 00:18:08.720
And actually during
the 1970s, he

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:11.680
spent a fair amount of his
time trying to defend himself

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:14.140
and to make the
case that there was

00:18:14.140 --> 00:18:17.290
a rational basis for his
ideas about population control

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:19.370
and also control of immigration.

00:18:19.370 --> 00:18:21.880
So these are two books that
he published during the '70s.

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:25.230
One, "The Race Bomb," which
basically said that race is,

00:18:25.230 --> 00:18:29.600
from a biological perspective,
not a meaningful category.

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:31.880
And so we shouldn't think
about racial differences.

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:33.660
And "The Golden
Door," which analyzed

00:18:33.660 --> 00:18:35.940
Mexican-American relations
and made the case

00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:39.690
that we shouldn't blame Mexican
immigrants but at the same time

00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:41.990
there was still a rational
basis or rational reason

00:18:41.990 --> 00:18:43.590
for wanting to
limit immigration.

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.090
So this was a lot
of his efforts was

00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:47.972
trying to navigate those
complicated politics.

00:18:47.972 --> 00:18:50.180
Now, I wanted to give you
a bit of a taste of Ehrlich

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:51.590
and Simon.

00:18:51.590 --> 00:18:55.100
If it will work, I have
a little video here

00:18:55.100 --> 00:18:56.870
to share just to give
you a bit of a sense

00:18:56.870 --> 00:19:00.590
of their rhetorical styles
and some of their arguments.

00:19:00.590 --> 00:19:03.685
So this is Ehrlich
in 1971, I believe,

00:19:03.685 --> 00:19:07.520
on an Australian television
show called "Monday Conference."

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:08.186
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:19:08.186 --> 00:19:11.620
-I wonder if we could
begin at the end in a way.

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:14.550
One of the things that
Dr. Ehrlich is saying

00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:19.350
is that things are so bad
that people should not

00:19:19.350 --> 00:19:24.229
be allowed to have as many
children as they may now want.

00:19:24.229 --> 00:19:25.270
What do we think of this?

00:19:25.270 --> 00:19:28.730
Does anyone have a
comment on that or--

00:19:28.730 --> 00:19:32.450
-While I'm very intrigued
by Dr. Ehrlich's concern

00:19:32.450 --> 00:19:34.800
for the environment,
for our future,

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:38.180
I'm quite appalled at the
"1984" style of society

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:41.260
that he postulates in his books.

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:45.180
He would seem to cut right
across inalienable human rights

00:19:45.180 --> 00:19:51.570
and demand that people be
legalized to produce children.

00:19:51.570 --> 00:19:54.360
He would tend to demand
that we limit our families

00:19:54.360 --> 00:19:56.120
and, if people are
not willing to do this

00:19:56.120 --> 00:19:59.550
by propaganda-- propaganda
principally aimed

00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:02.700
at the impoverished people
and at the dark races--

00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:04.750
he would introduce
legal sanctions.

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:06.290
Having introduced
legal sanctions,

00:20:06.290 --> 00:20:08.650
what legal penalties
for those who

00:20:08.650 --> 00:20:11.840
disobey the law of the
scientists, compulsory abortion

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:12.985
or imprisonment?

00:20:12.985 --> 00:20:15.360
Well, let me first point out
that you have misrepresented

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:17.860
my views somewhat, although you
have come close in other areas.

00:20:17.860 --> 00:20:19.360
Like, one of the
things that we have

00:20:19.360 --> 00:20:21.712
to face very clearly is
the question, if we do not

00:20:21.712 --> 00:20:23.920
solve this problem by finding
ways to change people's

00:20:23.920 --> 00:20:25.780
attitudes, what
kinds of sanctions

00:20:25.780 --> 00:20:29.215
might you impose that do
not bear differentially

00:20:29.215 --> 00:20:31.590
on the poor or the black or
the nations in the world that

00:20:31.590 --> 00:20:35.040
are underdeveloped and so on?

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:38.120
And this is an area where the
questions are very difficult.

00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:41.062
And, actually, in many
ways, the best answer

00:20:41.062 --> 00:20:42.520
from the point of
view of democracy

00:20:42.520 --> 00:20:44.970
seems to be an
across-the-board limitation

00:20:44.970 --> 00:20:49.350
of family size to two children
unless the second birth is

00:20:49.350 --> 00:20:50.890
a multiple birth.

00:20:50.890 --> 00:20:52.890
Now, you say these are
inalienable rights.

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:56.605
A favorite sport of people is
to make up inalienable rights

00:20:56.605 --> 00:20:58.384
to fit their own preconceptions.

00:20:58.384 --> 00:20:59.800
I say there's an
inalienable right

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:00.990
to have grandchildren
that you'll

00:21:00.990 --> 00:21:02.614
abrogate if you have
too many children.

00:21:02.614 --> 00:21:05.080
There's an inalienable
right to have clean air,

00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:06.090
not to breathe poisons.

00:21:06.090 --> 00:21:08.020
There's an inalienable right
to have natural beauty,

00:21:08.020 --> 00:21:09.740
to have enough food,
and so on, and so forth.

00:21:09.740 --> 00:21:11.525
now there was a time
when people thought

00:21:11.525 --> 00:21:13.900
it was an inalienable right
to have the number of spouses

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:15.114
that they chose to have.

00:21:15.114 --> 00:21:17.280
And certainly no government
could intervene on that,

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:19.696
but I believe the Australian
government intervenes on that

00:21:19.696 --> 00:21:22.170
inalienable right and restricts
you to one spouse at a time

00:21:22.170 --> 00:21:24.690
and throws you probably
right into jail if you don't.

00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:25.760
So I suspect that
could easily happen

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:27.560
with the number of
children you have too.

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:28.450
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:21:28.450 --> 00:21:30.760
PAUL SABIN: So in addition
to the marvelous sideburns

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:32.990
that he is displaying
here, I think

00:21:32.990 --> 00:21:35.590
there are another couple of
interesting elements of this.

00:21:35.590 --> 00:21:37.500
You can see here the rhetoric.

00:21:37.500 --> 00:21:41.770
We have to take action now
or disaster will come later.

00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:44.920
And sort of a grandiose
vision of that--

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:47.484
you're going to abrogate your
right to have grandchildren

00:21:47.484 --> 00:21:48.650
if we don't take action now.

00:21:48.650 --> 00:21:52.370
So it's a very stark portrayal.

00:21:52.370 --> 00:21:54.020
You can see, again,
this issue of him

00:21:54.020 --> 00:21:57.340
trying to develop a rational
basis for population control,

00:21:57.340 --> 00:21:59.350
defending against the
criticism that this might

00:21:59.350 --> 00:22:02.060
be racist or
inequitable and trying

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:05.445
to create a fair way to
have population control.

00:22:05.445 --> 00:22:06.820
And I think another
element there

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:09.420
that you can see here is just
the sharp rhetorical style,

00:22:09.420 --> 00:22:12.600
the humor, the ability to
take convey the argument that

00:22:12.600 --> 00:22:16.930
is quite compelling as
a presentation style.

00:22:16.930 --> 00:22:19.340
Now, here Ehrlich is
sporting sideburns.

00:22:19.340 --> 00:22:23.520
Here is Julian Simon
sporting his own flourish.

00:22:23.520 --> 00:22:28.039
He liked to wear these
plastic devil horns sometimes

00:22:28.039 --> 00:22:28.830
when he gave talks.

00:22:28.830 --> 00:22:31.700
It was kind of a
provocation of his audience.

00:22:31.700 --> 00:22:35.150
You portray me as the devil
with these terrible ideas

00:22:35.150 --> 00:22:37.572
that I have and so I'm going
to stick it in your face

00:22:37.572 --> 00:22:38.780
by wearing these devil horns.

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:41.150
I think it was also maybe a
bit of a defensive mechanism

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:42.860
that he used to protect himself.

00:22:42.860 --> 00:22:44.840
But here he is laying
out his arguments

00:22:44.840 --> 00:22:49.100
for why he thinks we don't face
a threat of resource scarcity

00:22:49.100 --> 00:22:50.780
and why he thinks
things are just

00:22:50.780 --> 00:22:53.274
going to keep on getting better.

00:22:53.274 --> 00:22:54.190
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:22:54.190 --> 00:22:56.710
-Every trend in
material human welfare

00:22:56.710 --> 00:22:59.075
has been getting better
rather than worse.

00:22:59.075 --> 00:23:01.280
And as to the future, you
ask, would I bet on it?

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:03.350
The answer is, yes.

00:23:03.350 --> 00:23:04.685
I will bet on it.

00:23:04.685 --> 00:23:08.140
I make this offer to any
prominent doom-sayer.

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:12.560
You pick any measure of
material human welfare,

00:23:12.560 --> 00:23:16.190
you pick any place in
the world, any country,

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:18.440
you pick any year in the
future, starting, say,

00:23:18.440 --> 00:23:21.110
10 years from now so there's
time for things to happen,

00:23:21.110 --> 00:23:26.240
and I'm prepared to bet that
that dimension that you pick,

00:23:26.240 --> 00:23:28.460
that aspect of human
welfare you pick,

00:23:28.460 --> 00:23:32.750
will show improvement relative
to now and not deterioration.

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:39.300
Now, before we go
on, let me give you

00:23:39.300 --> 00:23:42.210
the theory of how this could
possibly happen in a nutshell.

00:23:42.210 --> 00:23:45.177
And I'll repeat this
theory later on.

00:23:45.177 --> 00:23:46.260
The theory goes like this.

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:50.060
You have more people,
you have higher income,

00:23:50.060 --> 00:23:53.800
and that increases the
demand for resources.

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:57.420
Increased demand for resources
means higher prices, either

00:23:57.420 --> 00:24:00.150
actual or expected.

00:24:00.150 --> 00:24:03.840
Now that's as far as the
Malthusian theory goes,

00:24:03.840 --> 00:24:07.030
but the economy
doesn't stop there.

00:24:07.030 --> 00:24:08.930
What happens is
that these expected

00:24:08.930 --> 00:24:12.900
higher prices
represent opportunity.

00:24:12.900 --> 00:24:15.560
They represent
opportunity to businesses.

00:24:15.560 --> 00:24:17.710
Businesses say,
aha, higher prices.

00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:19.250
Greater opportunities
for profit.

00:24:19.250 --> 00:24:22.000
I'll get to work and see
if I can find some way

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:26.910
to increase my supply or
find substitutes or whatever.

00:24:26.910 --> 00:24:29.980
It also represents
opportunity for scientists,

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:32.830
who say, here's a chance for
me to make a discovery that

00:24:32.830 --> 00:24:36.410
will help humanity, maybe
even get a Nobel Prize for it.

00:24:36.410 --> 00:24:37.510
So that's the theory.

00:24:37.510 --> 00:24:40.540
But one more bit.

00:24:40.540 --> 00:24:46.590
So people go to work looking for
ways to fill this opportunity.

00:24:46.590 --> 00:24:49.550
Most of them fail.

00:24:49.550 --> 00:24:51.840
They don't find
solutions to the problem,

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:55.000
but they pay the
price themselves.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.080
Eventually, some
people do succeed

00:24:58.080 --> 00:25:01.100
in finding solutions
to these problems.

00:25:01.100 --> 00:25:04.540
And the extraordinary part is
that the solutions that they

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:09.310
find leave us better off
than if the problem had not

00:25:09.310 --> 00:25:11.584
arisen in the first place.

00:25:11.584 --> 00:25:12.940
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:25:12.940 --> 00:25:16.880
