Simon's response to Ehrlich.

00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:19.220
And some of this is some
basic economic theory,

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:23.080
ideas about technological
substitution, innovation,

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:26.840
the spur to investment, the
search for new resources.

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:28.590
You also can see,
in Simon, he has

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:30.070
some of the same
rhetorical style

00:25:30.070 --> 00:25:33.360
as Ehrlich in the sense of
a kind of combativeness.

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:33.940
I'll bet you.

00:25:33.940 --> 00:25:36.250
I'll challenge you.

00:25:36.250 --> 00:25:37.830
A similar aggressiveness.

00:25:37.830 --> 00:25:41.950
And also a tendency towards, not
just that things are generally

00:25:41.950 --> 00:25:44.190
getting better, but an
extreme version of that

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:46.010
in which every
single thing is going

00:25:46.010 --> 00:25:49.520
to be getting better
all across society.

00:25:49.520 --> 00:25:53.050
So that's a portrayal of Simon.

00:25:53.050 --> 00:25:54.655
And now I want to
turn now to what

00:25:54.655 --> 00:25:56.810
I think is an interesting
element of the story.

00:25:56.810 --> 00:25:58.510
So they make the bet in 1980.

00:25:58.510 --> 00:26:01.092
And that's actually only one
of the bets that's in my book.

00:26:01.092 --> 00:26:03.050
The second bet is the
other bet that the nation

00:26:03.050 --> 00:26:06.450
was making in 1980 which was
the choice between Jimmy Carter

00:26:06.450 --> 00:26:08.330
and Ronald Reagan in
the 1980 election.

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:10.980
I think in interesting
ways, the arguments

00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:14.580
between Ehrlich and
Simon actually line up

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:20.280
in striking ways with the
division between Carter

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:21.345
and Reagan.

00:26:21.345 --> 00:26:25.630
Now, Carter really brought
the Ehrlich perspective

00:26:25.630 --> 00:26:27.450
into the White House
in a lot of ways.

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:30.610
He embraced the idea of
conservation and limits.

00:26:30.610 --> 00:26:33.830
Here he is walking,
after his inauguration,

00:26:33.830 --> 00:26:36.410
walking the distance
to the White House.

00:26:36.410 --> 00:26:41.350
And here installing the
solar panels on a roof

00:26:41.350 --> 00:26:42.770
in the White House.

00:26:42.770 --> 00:26:46.180
And he talked about how,
even our great nation

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:47.620
has its recognized limits.

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:49.970
More is not necessarily better.

00:26:49.970 --> 00:26:54.400
And he closely shared a lot of
the key philosophical elements,

00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:58.010
I think, of the 1970s
environmental sensibility.

00:26:58.010 --> 00:27:01.360
He had a passion for nature
as a child in Georgia.

00:27:01.360 --> 00:27:03.280
He had fished and
hunted in the streams.

00:27:03.280 --> 00:27:06.290
And, as governor, he had
protected a lot of open space

00:27:06.290 --> 00:27:08.040
and tired to coordinate
regional planning

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:13.000
to be more rational
and more conserving.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.930
He had a moral righteousness
that Ehrlich also has,

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:17.790
a moral righteousness
about the need

00:27:17.790 --> 00:27:21.110
to address human excess
and human wastefulness.

00:27:21.110 --> 00:27:23.530
And he had a conviction
that government planning

00:27:23.530 --> 00:27:26.480
was the proper way to
respond and to address

00:27:26.480 --> 00:27:28.080
social and
environmental planners.

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:32.050
And Carter actually got his
start with regional planning

00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:33.710
initiatives in
Georgia, and he brought

00:27:33.710 --> 00:27:36.940
this idea of planning
to the White House.

00:27:36.940 --> 00:27:40.770
He approached these
problems as a planner.

00:27:40.770 --> 00:27:42.460
So in this particular,
he was focused

00:27:42.460 --> 00:27:47.770
on the problem of energy
in the late 1970s.

00:27:47.770 --> 00:27:50.480
And he worried about how
the Americans were grossly

00:27:50.480 --> 00:27:53.500
wasting our energy resources
and other materials

00:27:53.500 --> 00:27:55.650
as though their
supply was infinite.

00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:58.390
But we must face the
prospect of changing

00:27:58.390 --> 00:28:00.640
our basic ways of living.

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:03.250
And he expressed
this in similar terms

00:28:03.250 --> 00:28:05.790
to Ehrlich, saying,
"this change will either

00:28:05.790 --> 00:28:08.840
be made in our own initiative
in a planned or rational way.

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:11.322
So that's Ehrlich's idea that
if you can take action now,

00:28:11.322 --> 00:28:13.030
then we can avoid
problems in the future.

00:28:13.030 --> 00:28:16.180
"Or changes will
inevitably," he said,

00:28:16.180 --> 00:28:18.890
"be forced on us with
chaos and suffering

00:28:18.890 --> 00:28:20.700
by the inexorable
laws of nature,"

00:28:20.700 --> 00:28:22.520
And so I think this
aligns in a lot

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:24.510
of ways with Ehrlich's ideas.

00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:27.060
And here, just to give you
a taste of Carter's take,

00:28:27.060 --> 00:28:31.990
this is him talking about
energy in April '77, April 1977

00:28:31.990 --> 00:28:35.394
speech addressed to the nation
on a proposed energy policy.

00:28:35.394 --> 00:28:36.060
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:28:36.060 --> 00:28:39.110
-The energy crisis has
not yet overwhelmed us,

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:42.854
but it will if we
do not act quickly.

00:28:42.854 --> 00:28:44.270
It's a problem
that we will not be

00:28:44.270 --> 00:28:46.860
able to solve in
the next few years.

00:28:46.860 --> 00:28:48.610
And it's likely to get
progressively worse

00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:51.460
through the rest
of this century.

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:55.150
We must not be
selfish or timid if we

00:28:55.150 --> 00:28:57.450
hope to have a decent
world for our children

00:28:57.450 --> 00:28:59.190
and our grandchildren.

00:28:59.190 --> 00:29:02.890
We simply must balance
our demand for energy

00:29:02.890 --> 00:29:06.030
with our rapidly
shrinking resources.

00:29:06.030 --> 00:29:08.680
By acting now, we can
control our future

00:29:08.680 --> 00:29:11.530
instead of letting
the future control us.

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:14.420
Two days from now, I will
present to the Congress

00:29:14.420 --> 00:29:16.480
my energy proposals.

00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:18.780
Its members will be my
partners and they have already

00:29:18.780 --> 00:29:22.270
given me a great deal
of valuable advice.

00:29:22.270 --> 00:29:25.780
Many of these proposals
will be unpopular.

00:29:25.780 --> 00:29:28.200
Some will cause you to
put up with inconveniences

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.014
and to make sacrifices.

00:29:30.014 --> 00:29:31.930
The most important thing
about these proposals

00:29:31.930 --> 00:29:37.630
is that the alternative may
be a national catastrophe.

00:29:37.630 --> 00:29:40.270
Further delay can affect
our strength and our power

00:29:40.270 --> 00:29:42.040
as a nation.

00:29:42.040 --> 00:29:44.130
Our decision about
energy will test

00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:46.389
the character of
the American people

00:29:46.389 --> 00:29:48.430
and the ability of the
president and the Congress

00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:50.440
to govern this nation.

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:53.790
This difficult effort will
be the moral equivalent.

00:29:53.790 --> 00:29:54.570
of war.

00:29:54.570 --> 00:29:55.403
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:29:55.403 --> 00:29:56.980
PAUL SABIN: So this
is Carter warning

00:29:56.980 --> 00:29:58.540
about national catastrophe.

00:29:58.540 --> 00:30:00.360
He worried that the US
was going to run out

00:30:00.360 --> 00:30:03.960
of oil reserves in the
1980s and that disaster

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:05.690
was right around the corner.

00:30:05.690 --> 00:30:10.530
And this was sort of-- the
image that Carter presented

00:30:10.530 --> 00:30:12.030
to the country
was one of limits,

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:14.990
of the need for
sacrifice, and the need

00:30:14.990 --> 00:30:16.880
to address this with planning.

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:19.350
And that was something
that Ronald Reagan strongly

00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:23.520
objected to and came in
resisting that, running

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:27.600
for office on the promise
of American greatness.

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:29.870
And he to a significant
extent, I think,

00:30:29.870 --> 00:30:32.920
sang to the tune
of Julian Simon.

00:30:32.920 --> 00:30:36.320
The idea that resource
limits weren't real,

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:38.790
that they wouldn't
constrain America's future.

00:30:38.790 --> 00:30:42.880
And this announcement for his
candidacy for the White House--

00:30:42.880 --> 00:30:46.310
I think it's striking
how much he focused

00:30:46.310 --> 00:30:48.830
in terms of the rationale
for his candidacy

00:30:48.830 --> 00:30:52.660
on the predictions that
the United States faced

00:30:52.660 --> 00:30:55.670
limits and doom and constraints.

00:30:55.670 --> 00:31:02.960
And I wanted to share with you
this clip from his announcement

00:31:02.960 --> 00:31:05.236
of the candidacy in 1979.

00:31:05.236 --> 00:31:06.056
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:31:06.056 --> 00:31:07.680
-Now there are those
in our land today,

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:10.670
however, who would have
us believe that the United

00:31:10.670 --> 00:31:13.970
States, like other great
civilizations of the past,

00:31:13.970 --> 00:31:16.120
has reached the
zenith of its power,

00:31:16.120 --> 00:31:18.840
that we're weak and fearful,
reduced to bickering

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:22.010
with each other and no
longer possessed of the will

00:31:22.010 --> 00:31:24.400
to cope with our problems.

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:27.455
Much of this talk
has come from leaders

00:31:27.455 --> 00:31:30.780
who claim that our problems
are too difficult to handle.

00:31:30.780 --> 00:31:33.820
We're supposed to meekly
accept their failures

00:31:33.820 --> 00:31:36.580
as the most which
can humanly be done.

00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:39.470
They tell us we must
learn to live with less

00:31:39.470 --> 00:31:42.140
and teach our children that
their lives will be less

00:31:42.140 --> 00:31:44.500
full and prosperous
than ours have been,

00:31:44.500 --> 00:31:46.880
that the America
of the coming years

00:31:46.880 --> 00:31:50.550
will be a place where,
because of our past excesses,

00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:52.920
it will be impossible
to dream and make

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:55.560
those dreams come true.

00:31:55.560 --> 00:31:59.760
I don't believe that, and I
don't believe you do either.

00:31:59.760 --> 00:32:02.450
That's why I'm seeking
the presidency.

00:32:02.450 --> 00:32:06.400
I cannot and will not stand
by and see this great country

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:08.470
destroy itself.

00:32:08.470 --> 00:32:11.390
Our leaders attempt to blame
their failures on circumstances

00:32:11.390 --> 00:32:14.500
beyond their control,
on false estimates

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:17.510
by unknown unidentifiable
experts who

00:32:17.510 --> 00:32:20.040
rewrite modern
history in an attempt

00:32:20.040 --> 00:32:22.810
to convince us our high
standard of living--

00:32:22.810 --> 00:32:25.030
the result of thrift
and hard work--

00:32:25.030 --> 00:32:27.940
is somehow selfish
extravagance which

00:32:27.940 --> 00:32:32.520
we must renounce as we
join in sharing scarcity.

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:33.460
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:32:33.460 --> 00:32:35.918
PAUL SABIN: Now, Reagan doesn't
specify who these anonymous

00:32:35.918 --> 00:32:39.410
experts are, but I would argue
that he's referring to people

00:32:39.410 --> 00:32:42.590
like Paul Ehrlich and also the
authors of the 1972 book "The

00:32:42.590 --> 00:32:46.120
Limits to Growth" who had
run these computer models

00:32:46.120 --> 00:32:50.720
of resources and the economy
and population and said that--

00:32:50.720 --> 00:32:53.880
in a similar story to
Ehrlich's-- that we were going

00:32:53.880 --> 00:32:58.240
to have a population overshoot
and then a collapse more

00:32:58.240 --> 00:33:00.480
or less right around
now or in another decade

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:05.810
or so in the 21st century.

00:33:05.810 --> 00:33:07.670
So Reagan came in
and he used this

00:33:07.670 --> 00:33:12.740
is new idea about how we
didn't face fundamental limits

00:33:12.740 --> 00:33:16.490
or scarcity as a
rationale, a justification,

00:33:16.490 --> 00:33:18.200
for regulatory relief.

00:33:18.200 --> 00:33:21.380
He set up a vice presidential
commission on regulatory relief

00:33:21.380 --> 00:33:23.710
and instructed the Office
of Management and Budget

00:33:23.710 --> 00:33:26.780
to apply new tests
to try to do what

00:33:26.780 --> 00:33:30.150
David Stockman, the head
of the budget office,

00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:34.000
said was a regulatory
ventilation, was the language.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:35.794
But the idea was really
to try to reversal

00:33:35.794 --> 00:33:38.210
a lot of the regulations that
had been passed in the '70s.

00:33:38.210 --> 00:33:44.110
And so the bipartisanship
era of environmental policy

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:46.126
was truly over at this point.

00:33:46.126 --> 00:33:47.500
The environmental
groups attacked

00:33:47.500 --> 00:33:50.200
Reagan and I think
the partisanship

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:53.200
that we have come to see
really settled in quite fully.

00:33:53.200 --> 00:33:58.060
And it centered in some ways
I think on the questions that

00:33:58.060 --> 00:34:00.190
were at the heart of the
Ehrlich and Simon bet

00:34:00.190 --> 00:34:04.450
which is, does the
US, does the planet,

00:34:04.450 --> 00:34:06.240
face an environmental crisis?

00:34:06.240 --> 00:34:09.840
Were we running out of resources
and compelled to conserve?

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:16.159
And what were the natural
limits of American growth?

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:18.969
So in October
1990, Julian Simon,

00:34:18.969 --> 00:34:22.780
having moved to Maryland,
picked up his mail and opened up

00:34:22.780 --> 00:34:24.750
and there was a sheet
of metal prices in there

00:34:24.750 --> 00:34:28.429
with a check for $576.07.

00:34:28.429 --> 00:34:30.179
And there was no
note, but it was

00:34:30.179 --> 00:34:32.699
clear the check was
from Paul Ehrlich

00:34:32.699 --> 00:34:35.790
to settle the bet on the metals.

00:34:35.790 --> 00:34:39.409
The metals fallen, on
average, by around 50%,

00:34:39.409 --> 00:34:42.579
so Simon prevailing
across the board.

00:34:42.579 --> 00:34:44.870
And it's interesting to think
about why that turned out

00:34:44.870 --> 00:34:46.409
to be the case.

00:34:46.409 --> 00:34:52.030
In part, it was the collapse
of oil prices after 1979,

00:34:52.030 --> 00:34:53.780
but you also had all
these different kinds

00:34:53.780 --> 00:34:56.880
of everyday market forces which
were the very kinds of things

00:34:56.880 --> 00:34:59.470
that Simon and other
economists had talked about,

00:34:59.470 --> 00:35:03.080
the substitution of new
technologies like fiber

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:06.320
optic cables and satellites
for copper wires,

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:10.090
the breakup of the
tin cartel, which

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:11.800
had propped up tin prices.

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:14.960
And when it collapsed, the
prices fell through the floor.

00:35:14.960 --> 00:35:16.470
You had new sources
of supply that

00:35:16.470 --> 00:35:18.950
were brought on because higher
prices stimulated people

00:35:18.950 --> 00:35:21.040
to go out to search
for new mines.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:23.350
You had the break up
of labor conflicts

00:35:23.350 --> 00:35:25.980
that had sent prices
higher in the late '70s,

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:28.810
and then when those
conflicts were resolved,

00:35:28.810 --> 00:35:30.210
prices went down.

00:35:30.210 --> 00:35:32.060
So in all these
different ways, you

00:35:32.060 --> 00:35:34.940
had these everyday market
forces, the kinds of things

00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:39.970
that Simon had talked about.

00:35:39.970 --> 00:35:45.110
But even more generally than
the prices of metal-- the thing

00:35:45.110 --> 00:35:47.230
to note is the
worldwide population

00:35:47.230 --> 00:35:49.500
had grown by 800 million
during this period,

00:35:49.500 --> 00:35:55.650
from a from 4.5 to
5.3 billion people,

00:35:55.650 --> 00:35:58.950
to date the largest
increase over a decade.

00:35:58.950 --> 00:36:06.250
And yet the metal
prices had still fallen.

00:36:06.250 --> 00:36:08.000
More broadly, in
thinking about the bet--

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:10.260
so the bet was a proxy for
a larger bet, which is,

00:36:10.260 --> 00:36:12.380
what was going to be
the fate of humanity?

00:36:12.380 --> 00:36:14.460
Measures of human
health and human wealth

00:36:14.460 --> 00:36:18.960
also have increased over
time during that time period

00:36:18.960 --> 00:36:21.920
and on up until the
present time as well.

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:24.160
I don't if any of you have
ever seen Hans Roslings

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:27.240
interesting videos about
human history in four minutes.

00:36:27.240 --> 00:36:30.780
He has this great video in which
he explains the improvements

00:36:30.780 --> 00:36:36.650
in health and wealth over the
last couple hundred years.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:39.930
So at first glance, the results
of the Ehrlich Simon bet

00:36:39.930 --> 00:36:41.740
seem to suggest a
simple story line.

00:36:41.740 --> 00:36:44.180
There's a clear winner
and a clear loser.

00:36:44.180 --> 00:36:47.630
And the bet itself quickly
became a symbolic weapon

00:36:47.630 --> 00:36:49.820
in battles between
conservatives and liberals

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:51.710
over environmental
policy, saying, look,

00:36:51.710 --> 00:36:54.440
Simon won this bet
so environmentalists

00:36:54.440 --> 00:36:57.075
are wrong about this
and everything else.

00:36:57.075 --> 00:36:59.500
And so this is the
reason for opposing

00:36:59.500 --> 00:37:02.090
all different kinds
of regulation.

00:37:02.090 --> 00:37:04.595
And so is it a symbol
of its symbolic value.

00:37:04.595 --> 00:37:06.720
The Competitive Enterprise
Institute, for instance,

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:10.130
today awards a Julian
Simon award for someone

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:14.990
who is contributing to our
appreciation of the powers

00:37:14.990 --> 00:37:16.850
of human ingenuity
and innovation.

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:22.670
And the award is
a leaf-- I'm not

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:24.837
sure what the main
part of the leaf

00:37:24.837 --> 00:37:26.420
is made of-- but the
veins of the leaf

00:37:26.420 --> 00:37:30.170
are the five metals from
the Ehrlich Simon bet

00:37:30.170 --> 00:37:36.160
so it's sort of just the
symbolic power of the bet

00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:36.840
itself.

00:37:36.840 --> 00:37:39.430
But I think that
story of Simon wins,

00:37:39.430 --> 00:37:43.120
Ehrlich loses is too simple
an interpretation of this bet

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:46.986
and of the larger clash
between Ehrlich and Simon.

00:37:46.986 --> 00:37:48.610
Because while measures
of human welfare

00:37:48.610 --> 00:37:52.850
have improved in recent
decades, the planet's ecosystems

00:37:52.850 --> 00:37:55.620
are also under more
stress than ever before.

00:37:55.620 --> 00:37:57.120
You have global
temperatures rising,

00:37:57.120 --> 00:37:59.490
fish stocks being depleted.

00:37:59.490 --> 00:38:02.790
And the quest to meet the
resource demands to avoid

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:05.350
facing scarcity have pushed
us into more and more risky

00:38:05.350 --> 00:38:08.150
practices, from blowing up
the mountains of Appalachia

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:11.220
in mountaintop removal mining
or going out into deep water oil

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:14.536
drilling leading to the
disastrous spill that

00:38:14.536 --> 00:38:16.160
took place in the
Gulf, a whole variety

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:20.560
of different challenges-- risks
that we're taking in order

00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:25.991
to avoid the scarcity that
Ehrlich like was warning of.

00:38:25.991 --> 00:38:27.490
Ehrlich and his
allies have insisted

00:38:27.490 --> 00:38:29.600
that the bet doesn't
prove anything.

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:32.772
He says Julian Simon is like
the guy who jumps off the Empire

00:38:32.772 --> 00:38:34.730
State Building and says
how great everything is

00:38:34.730 --> 00:38:39.180
as he passes the 10th floor
of the building going down.

00:38:39.180 --> 00:38:40.780
So Simon's actual
victory of the bet

00:38:40.780 --> 00:38:43.440
also has come under
attack because economists

00:38:43.440 --> 00:38:44.940
have gone back and
they have charted

00:38:44.940 --> 00:38:47.630
the prices of metals
going back to 1900.

00:38:47.630 --> 00:38:49.240
And they found that
actually if you

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:54.140
were to run this bet in
1900 to 1910, 1901 to 1911,

00:38:54.140 --> 00:38:56.120
Ehrlich actually would
have won more times

00:38:56.120 --> 00:38:57.220
than he would have lost.

00:38:57.220 --> 00:39:01.310
So the idea that Simon's
victory between 1980 1990

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:03.530
symbolizes that
prices of resources

00:39:03.530 --> 00:39:05.050
are always going
to go down, that's

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:09.320
actually not borne out over
the course of this history.

00:39:09.320 --> 00:39:13.570
But this data,
though, also, I think,

00:39:13.570 --> 00:39:17.420
is complicated because it
doesn't show either a clear

00:39:17.420 --> 00:39:20.616
rise or a clear drop
over the period of time.

00:39:20.616 --> 00:39:21.990
And, in fact, most
of the reasons

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:24.370
why Ehrlich would have
won over this time period

00:39:24.370 --> 00:39:26.720
is the recovery from
the tremendous collapse

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:31.230
in commodity prices after World
War I and then, eventually,

00:39:31.230 --> 00:39:36.070
the recovery of those prices.

00:39:36.070 --> 00:39:38.420
I think what it
suggests most of all

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:41.480
is how unreliable
commodity prices are

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:44.740
as a proxy for trying to
assess either the well

00:39:44.740 --> 00:39:48.475
being of humanity or the state
of the planet's ecosystems.

00:39:51.370 --> 00:39:55.000
So instead of being a
simple morality tale,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.540
I think that the story of
Ehrlich and Simon's bet

00:39:57.540 --> 00:39:59.250
reveals limitations
on both sides

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:00.895
of the environmental debate.

00:40:00.895 --> 00:40:03.420
And I think the stark
framing that both men

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:06.260
chose has made a
productive conversation

00:40:06.260 --> 00:40:09.390
about environmental problems
even more difficult.

00:40:09.390 --> 00:40:13.150
And rather than choose between
these competing perspectives,

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:14.827
what I think that
we need to do is

00:40:14.827 --> 00:40:16.910
to wrestle with the tensions
and the uncertainties

00:40:16.910 --> 00:40:20.130
that they raise and to try to
gain from the insights that

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:22.880
come from both the
economic side and also

00:40:22.880 --> 00:40:26.910
the insights of the biologists.

00:40:26.910 --> 00:40:29.490
So I wanted to close
with a few lessons

00:40:29.490 --> 00:40:34.052
that I think each side of this
conversation might take away.

00:40:34.052 --> 00:40:36.510
One of the main lessons for
environmentalists from the bet,

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:40.431
I think, is the power of human
adaptability and creativity.

00:40:40.431 --> 00:40:41.930
So environmentalists
have often been

00:40:41.930 --> 00:40:45.480
prone to these kinds of
pessimistic predictions

00:40:45.480 --> 00:40:48.420
about the terrible catastrophe
there's right around the corner

00:40:48.420 --> 00:40:49.420
if we don't take action.

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:54.924
That has been the rhetoric of
many like Ehrlich since 1960s

00:40:54.924 --> 00:40:57.090
or you could say it even
goes back further to people

00:40:57.090 --> 00:41:02.340
like Malthus much earlier.

00:41:02.340 --> 00:41:06.840
But I think that
this clearly has not

00:41:06.840 --> 00:41:08.660
been the case in recent times.

00:41:08.660 --> 00:41:11.850
And I think that the
environmental community

00:41:11.850 --> 00:41:14.190
has to figure out how to
wrestle with that contradiction

00:41:14.190 --> 00:41:17.174
of the disaster not
having come yet.

00:41:17.174 --> 00:41:18.590
And what does that
mean for how we

00:41:18.590 --> 00:41:20.930
think about
environmental problems?

00:41:20.930 --> 00:41:25.110
And these sweeping apocalyptic
pronouncements themselves

00:41:25.110 --> 00:41:27.010
also carry risks
because they make

00:41:27.010 --> 00:41:31.720
it more difficult to achieve
pragmatic policy making.

00:41:31.720 --> 00:41:34.350
If you're warning of
the end of civilization,

00:41:34.350 --> 00:41:37.510
it makes it very hard to come
up with a pragmatic solution

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:42.890
around emissions trading,
around pollution credits,

00:41:42.890 --> 00:41:44.330
for instance, things like that.

00:41:44.330 --> 00:41:47.510
And I think that the
dire rhetoric also

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:50.630
makes it very difficult
for the followers of people

00:41:50.630 --> 00:41:52.930
like Ehrlich to be willing
to accept compromise

00:41:52.930 --> 00:42:00.060
and to be willing
to-- it creates

00:42:00.060 --> 00:42:02.490
unrealistic expectations
of what policies are going

00:42:02.490 --> 00:42:04.890
to accomplish in a
short period of time.

00:42:04.890 --> 00:42:07.480
The second inside I think
for the environmental side

00:42:07.480 --> 00:42:09.910
of this debate is
the way in which

00:42:09.910 --> 00:42:12.880
the debate itself--
overpopulation growth

00:42:12.880 --> 00:42:17.030
and resource scarcity-- has
a legacy and it matters.

00:42:17.030 --> 00:42:20.440
Because a lot of the
skepticism towards climate

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:22.450
change that you
see today I think

00:42:22.450 --> 00:42:25.830
is fueled in part by the
legacy of these past debates

00:42:25.830 --> 00:42:27.830
over resource scarcity
and population growth.

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:29.710
And people say,
look, Ehrlich was

00:42:29.710 --> 00:42:32.354
wrong about the predictions.
"The Limits of Growth,"

00:42:32.354 --> 00:42:33.020
they were wrong.

00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:33.970
They said we were
going to run out

00:42:33.970 --> 00:42:36.320
of all these things by
all these previous dates.

00:42:36.320 --> 00:42:39.490
We didn't run out
of oil in the 1980s.

00:42:39.490 --> 00:42:42.140
Pollution's gotten
better rather than worse.

00:42:42.140 --> 00:42:44.620
All these different
ways-- predictions

00:42:44.620 --> 00:42:51.010
have not come true as were
expected or were predicted.

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:54.360
And so therefore we're now going
to doubt these new predictions.

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:56.955
So there's a lack
of credibility.

00:42:56.955 --> 00:43:00.770
And I think that,
for environmentalists

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:04.360
to understand the people who
they call climate deniers,

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:08.600
I think it's useful to
wrestle with this history,

00:43:08.600 --> 00:43:12.040
these debates over and kind of
to think a little bit more--

00:43:12.040 --> 00:43:13.540
again the empathy
that I was talking

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:16.206
about the beginning of the talk,
of trying to understand why you

00:43:16.206 --> 00:43:20.046
would see such skepticism
around the science.

00:43:20.046 --> 00:43:22.420
And I'm not saying that's the
only reason for skepticism.

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:24.400
There are many factors
going on but I believe

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:26.790
that wrestling with this
history of this debate

00:43:26.790 --> 00:43:32.780
is really-- has an impact
on our debate today.

00:43:32.780 --> 00:43:36.150
So now for conservative
followers of Julian Simon,

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:38.990
I think there are also
important lessons, one of which

00:43:38.990 --> 00:43:43.700
is just that past success is not
a guarantee of future success.

00:43:43.700 --> 00:43:47.680
And I think this often is
not adequately appreciated,

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:51.240
that our ability to adapt to
greater numbers of people,

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:54.040
our ability to find
new energy resources,

00:43:54.040 --> 00:43:56.537
those don't necessarily
mean that we

00:43:56.537 --> 00:43:58.120
are going to be able
to find solutions

00:43:58.120 --> 00:44:00.810
to the threat of climate change.

00:44:00.810 --> 00:44:05.490
And so just to assume that just
because we solved something

00:44:05.490 --> 00:44:07.227
in the past doesn't
mean we're going

00:44:07.227 --> 00:44:08.310
to solve it in the future.

00:44:08.310 --> 00:44:11.920
And I think that extends
to the second insight which

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:14.270
is that climate change is
different from population

00:44:14.270 --> 00:44:14.480
growth.

00:44:14.480 --> 00:44:15.771
These aren't the same problems.

00:44:15.771 --> 00:44:19.620
And so to say that we addressed
the growth of population,

00:44:19.620 --> 00:44:21.840
we were able to meet the
needs of growing population

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:24.830
doesn't necessarily have
similar implications for climate

00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:25.350
change.

00:44:25.350 --> 00:44:27.700
Climate change is a
very specific problem.

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:30.810
We're putting too much
of too many chemicals

00:44:30.810 --> 00:44:32.120
in the atmosphere.

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:34.540
In my view, it's a
pollution problem.

00:44:34.540 --> 00:44:37.310
Whereas population growth
is a very diffuse issue.

00:44:37.310 --> 00:44:39.570
There's many different
ways to feed people,

00:44:39.570 --> 00:44:44.010
to meet their energy needs, to
adapt to the diffuse pressures

00:44:44.010 --> 00:44:48.800
that more people put
on land and resources.

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:52.540
And those are in the marketplace
because people are out there

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:55.890
trying to consume things
and they're making demands

00:44:55.890 --> 00:44:58.060
and the marketplace
responds to those demands.

00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:01.060
And so the forces that
Julian Simon talked about,

00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:03.790
these market forces, can
respond to population growth.

00:45:03.790 --> 00:45:06.570
Whereas climate change
is, by very definition,

00:45:06.570 --> 00:45:09.270
it's outside of the marketplace
or it has been today.

00:45:09.270 --> 00:45:12.000
And until it is brought
within the marketplace,

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:16.646
those kinds of forces that
Simon's followers love to tout

00:45:16.646 --> 00:45:18.770
aren't really being brought
to bear on the problem.

00:45:18.770 --> 00:45:20.820
And that brings me
to the third insight

00:45:20.820 --> 00:45:24.240
I think that should be
shared with Simon's followers

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:26.100
which is that you
can't solve problems

00:45:26.100 --> 00:45:27.430
unless you acknowledge them.

00:45:27.430 --> 00:45:29.990
So Julian Simon in
that video I shared

00:45:29.990 --> 00:45:33.897
made the case that
problems rise up,

00:45:33.897 --> 00:45:35.480
we create solutions
to those problems,

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:37.063
and then we're better
off than before.

00:45:37.063 --> 00:45:39.494
But that's only if you
recognize that a problem exists.

00:45:39.494 --> 00:45:41.910
Because if you don't recognize
that a problem like climate

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:44.820
change exists, then you're not
bringing any of these forces

00:45:44.820 --> 00:45:46.620
to bear on solving the problem.

00:45:46.620 --> 00:45:50.120
And all of the science and
technology and innovation

00:45:50.120 --> 00:45:53.330
that may very well be able to
address the problem of climate

00:45:53.330 --> 00:45:56.430
change are not being
brought into play.

00:45:56.430 --> 00:46:01.190
And so I think that this is one
of the fundamental limitations,

00:46:01.190 --> 00:46:02.760
I think, of the
Simon perspective,

00:46:02.760 --> 00:46:06.910
which is that the very optimism
about the future itself

00:46:06.910 --> 00:46:12.660
becomes an inhibiting the
bringing about of that future

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:17.130
because an obstacle
to innovation.

00:46:17.130 --> 00:46:20.140
So now I want to return to my
first themes about listening

00:46:20.140 --> 00:46:23.710
and empathy and
complexity and questions,

00:46:23.710 --> 00:46:27.300
the kinds of learning I think
that history has to offer.

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:32.364
Because I think too often,
on both sides of this debate,

00:46:32.364 --> 00:46:33.780
both sides of this
debate have not

00:46:33.780 --> 00:46:35.450
been willing to
listen to each other.

00:46:35.450 --> 00:46:39.310
Ehrlich has bluntly
stated, including recently

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:43.410
in discussion of the
bet in an interview,

00:46:43.410 --> 00:46:46.580
that there's nothing to
learn from this story other

00:46:46.580 --> 00:46:50.330
than that it's a bad
idea to make bets.

00:46:50.330 --> 00:46:53.860
It was ill advised but he says
that it doesn't necessarily

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:57.564
signify anything about what's
happening in the future.

00:46:57.564 --> 00:46:59.230
And on the other hand,
Simon's followers

00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:01.390
act as if winning
this 10 year bet

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:03.820
signifies you're always
going to win the bet.

00:47:03.820 --> 00:47:05.490
There will never
be any problems.

00:47:05.490 --> 00:47:07.360
We're going to solve
all the problems.

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:10.360
And just because we
solved things in the past,

00:47:10.360 --> 00:47:14.710
no problems are going to come
up that we can't address.

00:47:14.710 --> 00:47:16.290
So I think both
of these positions

00:47:16.290 --> 00:47:19.630
are simplistic and wrong.

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:21.970
And that rather than
embrace either Ehrlich

00:47:21.970 --> 00:47:23.640
or Simon, what we
need to do is try

00:47:23.640 --> 00:47:25.390
to learn from their
insights, learn

00:47:25.390 --> 00:47:29.050
from both the tremendous
capacity for human adaptability

00:47:29.050 --> 00:47:31.800
and innovation, which Simon
I think give us insights

00:47:31.800 --> 00:47:36.210
into, and also the fragility
of the planet and the ways

00:47:36.210 --> 00:47:39.780
in which humans are transforming
the planet in more and more

00:47:39.780 --> 00:47:41.710
intense ways and
try to figure out

00:47:41.710 --> 00:47:43.960
how do we reconcile
and incorporate

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:47.310
these different things into a
coherent vision of the future.

00:47:47.310 --> 00:47:48.810
That's really I
believe what history

00:47:48.810 --> 00:47:52.290
has to offer in part is
this capacity for synthesis.

00:47:52.290 --> 00:47:55.500
And I think that, ultimately,
neither biology nor economics

00:47:55.500 --> 00:47:59.070
have the definitive answers
because, if you take

00:47:59.070 --> 00:48:03.270
the logic of these two men,
humans might survive along

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:06.670
the lines of Simon and we
might even prosper economically

00:48:06.670 --> 00:48:10.210
and in our health
while we also transform

00:48:10.210 --> 00:48:14.560
the planet in many of the ways
that Ehrlich has predicted.

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:17.780
So one of the
questions may be, then,

00:48:17.780 --> 00:48:20.970
do we want to live in
a more biologically

00:48:20.970 --> 00:48:25.670
impoverished planet but more
economically productive planet?

00:48:25.670 --> 00:48:29.990
So both these things could be
happening at the same time.

00:48:29.990 --> 00:48:31.710
So one lesson I think
from my story here

00:48:31.710 --> 00:48:33.420
is that humanities
course ultimately

00:48:33.420 --> 00:48:35.490
is going to be determined
less by the iron

00:48:35.490 --> 00:48:37.910
laws of nature that
Ehrlich liked to celebrate

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:43.230
or the unbounded market powers
that Simon embraced and more

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:46.280
by the social and political
choices that we have to make.

00:48:46.280 --> 00:48:49.860
And what we're faced
with is not a question

00:48:49.860 --> 00:48:53.810
of biology or economics in
looking into the future,

00:48:53.810 --> 00:48:55.370
but it's really
a social question

00:48:55.370 --> 00:48:57.580
about what kind of planet
do we want to live in.

00:48:57.580 --> 00:48:59.580
And that, I think, is a
fundamentally an ethical

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:01.300
question, and
that's really what I

00:49:01.300 --> 00:49:03.740
hope that we need to
take away from this story

00:49:03.740 --> 00:49:06.610
is how to wrestle
with that question

00:49:06.610 --> 00:49:09.620
and bring it back and take any
insights from Ehrlich and Simon

00:49:09.620 --> 00:49:11.619
to address those issues.

00:49:11.619 --> 00:49:13.160
So thank you very
much for listening,

00:49:13.160 --> 00:49:15.750
and happy to take any
questions that you might

00:49:15.750 --> 00:49:19.400
have about this
about this subject.

00:49:19.400 --> 00:49:22.280
[APPLAUSE]

