Report, "Limits to Growth,"

00:51:37.040 --> 00:51:39.990
and all of that and scared the
hell out of me a long time ago.

00:51:43.410 --> 00:51:46.040
Do you see a way that we can
bring our political discourse

00:51:46.040 --> 00:51:53.750
in this country and worldwide
to a more cooperative way

00:51:53.750 --> 00:51:56.770
of addressing problems rather
than being diametrically

00:51:56.770 --> 00:51:58.390
opposed?

00:51:58.390 --> 00:52:02.580
Dianne Feinstein versus
the senator from Oklahoma.

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:07.620
They're never going to
get together, but how can

00:52:07.620 --> 00:52:10.960
we move in that
direction of cooperation,

00:52:10.960 --> 00:52:13.890
focusing on solutions?

00:52:13.890 --> 00:52:17.090
Well that's a difficult
question and is really

00:52:17.090 --> 00:52:18.970
a fundamental
question of the day.

00:52:18.970 --> 00:52:22.400
I mean, as a historian,
one of my hopes

00:52:22.400 --> 00:52:25.420
is to contribute
to that by sharing

00:52:25.420 --> 00:52:28.080
this history of the
past debate in the hopes

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:31.290
that people can find
their way towards a more

00:52:31.290 --> 00:52:33.870
productive conversation and be
able to listen to each other

00:52:33.870 --> 00:52:34.570
better.

00:52:34.570 --> 00:52:37.020
But I think that
that's very optimistic

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:39.470
to think that a book
is going to do that.

00:52:39.470 --> 00:52:42.760
My own feeling about the
current state of affairs

00:52:42.760 --> 00:52:50.170
is that we're in a
specific moment in time.

00:52:50.170 --> 00:52:54.480
And I really am actually
optimistic that we will not

00:52:54.480 --> 00:52:58.300
be stuck in this
deadlock forever.

00:52:58.300 --> 00:53:02.560
My own feeling is that political
sentiment and popular sentiment

00:53:02.560 --> 00:53:07.350
around the question of climate
at some point will break.

00:53:07.350 --> 00:53:12.830
And at that point, it will move
into a pragmatic conversation

00:53:12.830 --> 00:53:17.180
around adaptation,
around different kinds

00:53:17.180 --> 00:53:19.470
of policies, pros and cons
of different strategies

00:53:19.470 --> 00:53:22.330
and approaches that
will be more productive.

00:53:22.330 --> 00:53:24.620
Not to say that it's
ever going to become easy

00:53:24.620 --> 00:53:28.070
but that it will be a more
pragmatic conversation, that we

00:53:28.070 --> 00:53:29.900
won't be stuck in this
particular moment.

00:53:29.900 --> 00:53:37.400
I don't feel that the current
political constellation

00:53:37.400 --> 00:53:42.090
is tenable as a
permanent status quo.

00:53:42.090 --> 00:53:45.700
Both the resistance to
the science of climate

00:53:45.700 --> 00:53:48.986
and resistance to
the ways in which

00:53:48.986 --> 00:53:50.610
it appears that the
climate is changing

00:53:50.610 --> 00:53:55.062
around us and the change
over generations of people

00:53:55.062 --> 00:53:56.770
and the different
ideas-- so I'm actually

00:53:56.770 --> 00:53:58.686
cautiously optimistic
that things will change.

00:53:58.686 --> 00:54:00.520
Whether it will
change in time for us

00:54:00.520 --> 00:54:05.070
to make a significant impact
on carbon emissions is unclear.

00:54:05.070 --> 00:54:09.160
But I have optimism actually
about the political debate

00:54:09.160 --> 00:54:12.480
to some extent, modest optimism.

00:54:12.480 --> 00:54:13.910
Thanks so much for coming.

00:54:13.910 --> 00:54:18.316
[APPLAUSE]

